Anonymous Tue 09 Jul 2019 16:31:56 No.24180795 Report
Quoted By: >>24181076
>>24180400
Writing is hard. It's easy to have a general idea, with rudimentary characters, and have that initial burst of creativity. That's the nature of starting a story. Things have an unrestrained quality to them, and you're putting out the stuff that was ate the forefront of your mind. But afterwards, you get into the nitty-gritty of it. You have to come up with new stuff in the constraints of your established plot and characters. There was to be some sense of progress. And the more you write, the more stuff you have to take into account.

It's easy to look at what you've written and start doubting yourself. To have that dread feeling that you've written yourself into a corner, or that you've said all you had to say. And with this genre (furry romance/erotica) it's easy to tell yourself you're already writing to spec, and not seriously, so you're going to cut yourself some slack. And that's fine. But under that veneer of carelessness you're still writing. It's the same craft, with the same inherent challenge.

And how many people are in that list, you suspect, who had little to no experience before starting on their respective stories?

You kinda hit the nail on the head - you'll actually see that in many modern, millennial relationships. My ideal mate would be my best friend. That's the kind of romantic relationship I like to write about. We're wired to want people with whom we can relate on several levels. Call it a stereotype, but that's why the "gamergirl" trope exists and is so prevalent in the sort of fiction you'll read here. It boils down to where and what you are. My favorite romance stories are usually coming of age type stories where childhood friends, a guy and a lady, "discover" one another in a way that evolves organically from a platonic relationship, if that makes sense. I like the chemistry I can depict when writing characters involved in relationships like that. They don't have to be 100% agreeable with one another or be behavioral doppelgangers, but the characters they've grown into from the point their story is set are polished from rubbing on one another over many years. Even their friction is interesting - what trials test characters like that, what sort of drama might unfold that can make them combative, distrustful, suspicious, or just plain, ol' angry with one another?

On one hand, I'd be quite happy with humans that look different and happen to be covered in fur (or whatever other material). Modern furfaggotry is mainly a cosmetic thing after all, and there's nothing wrong with an anthro character being little more than a reskinned human.
On the other hand, I also like anthros that are definitely not humans, but are still sapient creatures on the same mental playing field as us. In a galaxy of basic automatons and dumb animals capable of little more than basic problem solving on one hand, and possibly superintelligent AI, an entrenched galactic community of aliens that looks down on us as idiot children, and incomprehensible alien hiveminds and god-knows what else on the other hand, it's nice to imagine a "buddy" species to stand with us in a cold and uncaring galaxy. If our waifurs had strange genitalia, weird looking eyes, completely different facial expressions, and talked strangely because of the shape of their mouths, had strange needs and instincts based off their species, or whatever else, then I would still love them as long as we could communicate. Falling in love with such a creature and living with them is, in my mind, the highest form of expressing that "We're very different from each other, but you're still a person and I love you for it" concept.

I've got a couple of beers in me, so here's a shot. Mind that I'm not an expert writer, just about 100K words and most of that unreleased bc this novel keeps getting more complex

First, for people that haven't tried their hand yet.
Show and tell is a tricky thing, at least that's what I've found out by doing it. I've gained a large appreciation for people that do this for a living. Telling isn't bad, because you can infodump and make it part of the natural thoughts of a character. On the other hand, you can have dialogue that is like a boring class in school rather something that feels like actual people.

You've got a couple characters, some background, and you're setting a scene. The vibe I'm getting is your average highschool, cliqued to death and damned if you aren't going to say more about those scars by the time the length doubles.
Now the parts I'd work on if it was me. Highschools are chiched as fuckall, but most everyone's lived through part of it so hit the dynamics of your little world hard. Mr. hyena is a jilted (ex)boyfriend, and Ms. Hyena is sinking her claws in. Why? I find that when I'm outlining something or interrogating my characters motivations will I work at something else, asking the old who-what-when-why-how rattle out more questions until I see the plain & simple answer. So build on your characters, let them breathe, and let that world feel real and not like a newsprint comic.

Last, go back and edit yourself. I'm not saying you've got some glaring flaw, but that editing is much more difficult than the writing. Read through. Talk it out. Film it in your head. whatever it takes to give yourself perspective. You've got your main elements. Give me a variation on it, a short second scene between Mr. & Ms. Hyena. Maybe he makes a second friend that paints what you've written already from a different perspective. Hype up the real/unreal. Choose one element from a source and build a seed around it.
